There is evidence that you’re pointing at a real market force, though I’d frame it a bit more broadly than a single generation.

A few trends are converging:

* Nostalgia as emotional comfort. People often gravitate toward things that remind them of childhood during periods of uncertainty or rapid change.
* The first “digital native” adults. Many millennials and older Gen Z grew up with video games, anime, Pokémon, Disney, LEGO, Nickelodeon, etc. Those aren’t just kids’ brands anymore—they’re part of adult identity.
* Premium adult versions. Companies have learned that people will pay for higher-quality, better-designed versions of nostalgic products if they don’t feel childish.
* Social permission. Being an adult who enjoys hobbies once considered “for kids” has become much more culturally accepted.

We’ve already seen this with things like:

* Adult LEGO collections.
* High-end Pokémon card collecting.
* Designer sneakers inspired by cartoons.
* Retro gaming handhelds.
* Disney’s adult fan communities.
* Collectible vinyl figures.
* Luxury versions of classic toys and board games.

The opportunity, in my view, isn’t simply “make childhood things for adults.” It’s:

Translate childhood emotions into adult aesthetics and utility.

For example:

* A sophisticated desk lamp inspired by a favorite cartoon instead of a toy.
* Premium home décor with subtle references rather than overt branding.
* Clothing that only fellow fans recognize.
* Functional everyday carry inspired by fictional worlds.
* Wellness, fitness, or productivity products wrapped in nostalgic narratives.

One caution is that nostalgia can become saturated. The businesses that last usually don’t just resell the past—they use it as a bridge to create something genuinely useful or beautiful.

The phrase “Disney adults” has become shorthand online, but the broader phenomenon is that many adults maintain lifelong relationships with the media and symbols they grew up with. That’s likely to continue as those generations accumulate more spending power.

The enduring business opportunity is probably less about any one franchise and more about understanding a recurring pattern:

People don’t buy their childhood back—they buy the feeling their childhood gave them, reimagined for the life they live now.